            <p><b>28. Hydrolysis of salts, the degree of hydrolysis, its dependence from the concentration and the temperature, the hydrolysis constant. The role of hydrolysis in biochemical processes.</b></p>

            <p>Hydrolysis of salts is an interaction of salt ions with water leading to formation of slightly dissociated compounds, shifting the equilibrium of water dissociation and, as a rule, changing pH of the solution. In general case hydrolysis may be considered a reaction of substance decomposition by water (from the words hydro-water and lysis-decomposition). <br>
                Hydrolysis is a particular case of solvolysis that is interaction of a solute with a solvent.<br>
                Chemical compounds of different types can be subjected to hydrolysis: proteins, fats, carbohydrates, esters, salts, etc. In inorganic chemistry hydrolysis of salts occurs more often. <br>
                From the point of view of the Bronsted-Lowry theory, hydrolysis represents a particular case of reversible acid-base equilibrium. The mechanism of salt hydrolysis consists in interaction of salt ions (Lewis acid) with molecules of water (Lewis base) from the cluster of water molecules surrounding it. The stronger this interaction, the more intensive hydrolysis process.<br>
                Hydrolysis process consists in transition of protons:<br>
                a)from a water molecule to a salt anion, for example:<br>
                CO32- + HOH &harr;HCO3- + OH-;<br>
                b)from a cation to a water molecule, for example:<br>
                NH4+ + HOH &harr; NH3 + H3O+;<br>
                Four groups of salts may be distinguished:<br>
                &#61623;salts of strong acids and weak bases, for example, ammonium chloride;<br>
                &#61623;salts of strong bases and weak acids, for example, sodium nitrite;<br>
                &#61623;salts of weak acids and weak bases, for example, ammonium acetate;<br>
                &#61623;salts of strong acids and strong bases, for example, sodium chloride.<br>
                Hydrolysis is possible only for salts having cations of weak bases or anions of weak acids in their structure, exactly the salts of the first three groups.<br>
                Salts formed by a strong acid and strong base (NaCl, KNO, etc.) do not hydrolyze as ions of such salts do not form slightly dissociated compounds with water ions. In this case dissociation water equilibrium in the presence of salt does not shift, and solutions are practically neutral (pH=7). Salts of weak polybasic acids or multiacid bases hydrolyze step-wise, forming acidic or basic salts.<br>
                Quantitatively hydrolysis, as well as acid-base equilibrium, is characterized by the degree of hydrolysis &#945;h and the hydrolysis constant Kh.<br>
                The degree of salt hydrolysis is the ratio between the number of hydrolyzed molecules and the total number of molecules in a solution, or the ratio between the hydrolyzed salt concentration and the total salt concentration:<br>
                &#945;h= n(hydr.) / n(total), or &#945;h= c(hydr.) / c(total).<br>
                The degree of hydrolysis is expressed in fractions of unit or in percents. In solutions of the moderate concentration at room temperature, the degree of hydrolysis of the majority of salts is small. So, for 0.1 molar Na2CO3 solution at 298 K &#945;h= 2.7 %, and for 0.1 molar NaCN solution &#945;h= 1.5%.<br>
                The degree of hydrolysis depends on the nature of salts, their concentration and temperature. According to the mass action law, the degree of hydrolysis increases at dilution of solution. The qualitative influence of temperature on the degree of hydrolysis can be prognosticated based on Le Chatelier&rsquo;s principle. As the hydrolysis process in an endothermic process, according to Le Chatelier&rsquo;s principle, with rising of temperature the hydrolysis degree also increases.<br>
                Hydrolysis is related to energy metabolism and storage. All living cells require a continual supply of energy for two main purposes: the biosynthesis of micro and macromolecules, and the active transport of ions and molecules across cell membranes. The energy derived from the oxidation of nutrients is not used directly but, by means of a complex and long sequence of reactions, it is channelled into a special energy-storage molecule, adenosine triphosphate (ATP).<br>
                In addition, in living systems, most biochemical reactions (including ATP hydrolysis) take place during the catalysis of enzymes. The catalytic action of enzymes allows the hydrolysis of proteins, fats, oils, and carbohydrates.</p>

