            <p>Homogeneous catalysis are catalytic reactions where the catalyst is in the same phase as the reactants, so homogeneous catalysis applies to reactions in the gas phase and even in a solid. <br>
                Heterogenous catalysis is the alternative to homogeneous catalysis, where the catalysis occurs at the interface of two phases, typically gas-solid. <br>
                The mechanism of catalyst reaction depends on fact that catalyst decreases activation energy, what allows the reaction exist without using high temperature. The best example are metabolic processes in our organism. They need a lot of proteins to exist. Metabolic reactions would need really high temperature to work good, but proteins in temperature higher than 40 celsius degrees denature.<br>
