            <p>Chromatography is a physiochemical method of analysis and separarion of components of a mixture, based of their different distribution between two phases, on which is immobile (solid or liquid) and the other is mobile (gas or liquid), filtered through the immobile phase. <br>
                Acording to the aggregate state of phases, mobile and immobile (its it also called the stationary phase), gas and liquid types of chromatography are distinguished. &#96; <br>
                The mobile phase in gas chromatography is a gas carrier (hydrogen, helium, argon, nitrogen), to which a gaseous or vaporous mixture of analyzed substances is added. The immobile phase may be a non-volatile liquid (glycerin, polyethylene glycol), which is spread on a solid inert adsorbent (solid carrier). <br>
                The presence of components is the current gas carrier that goes out from the column is registered by a detector. Signals of the detector are written down as a chromatogram by an automatic potentiomer. A separate peak corresponds to each of the mixture components on the chromatogram. Modern detecors allow recording even 10-12 g of a substane. The described variety of gas chromatography is called gas-liguid chromatography, and the instrument that analyzes a mixture is named a gas chromatography. <br>
                If a solid adsorbent, not a liquid, is used as an immobile phase instead of a liquid, then such variant of chromatography is named gas adsorpion chromatography. As to liquid chromatography, a liquid is used as a mobile phase in this case, and the immobile phase is a liquid that is bounded to an inert solid support or a solid. Among liquid chromatography varieties of special sttention, according to medical and biological practise, in the method of high-performance liquid chromatography. In this method a mobile phase is a specially selected mixture of solvents which is introduced at a high pressure into a chromatographic column. Various chromatographic methods are also classified according to the technique of mixture components separation. There are may be column, capillary or planar chromatography. In column chromatography a mobile phase is passed through an immobile phase that fills the column. Capillary chromatpgraphy is based on the use a capillaries, in which a liquid immobile phase is applied to their inner walls and a mobile phase passed through it. In paper chromatography separation of a components mixture, which is in the liquid phase, takes place on a special prepared paper. Thin-layer chromatography is based on the use of a thin layer of solid material that is separed on a chromatographic plate made of an inert material (glass, aluminium, foil). Depending on the dominant mechanism of the process of mixture components separation, the chromatographic methods may be classified as : adsorption, partition, ion exchange, gel permeation, afiinity and thermochromatography. The essence of adsorption chromatography consist in separation of substances of mixtures based on their different adsorbability on that or another adsorbent. Ion exchange chromatogaphy is based a different ability of ions that are in the analyzed mixture to exchange with ions that enter into the composition of an ion exchanger. Separation of mixtures into their components by gel permeation chromatography, which is also called size exclusion or molecular sieve chromatography, is based on the different ability of substances to penetrate into porres of a gel that plays a role of the mobille phase. Afiinity chromatography is based on the abilities of some compounds to in a solution only their substances and to interact with them. Precipitation chromatography is based on a difference in the solubility of precipitates which are obtained as a result to chemical interaction of mixture components with a substance of the immobile phase. A chromatogram of human body metabolites gives a possibility to establish the type of microorganisms that have produced a disease. Chromatography has a great role in the diagnosis of congenital and acquired metabolism dysfunction, such as diabetes mellitus, podagra and other sidease. Chromatographic research of the lipid content in the blood have promoted the determination of the causes of origin, ways of prophylaxis and treatment of atherosclerosis, which is a disease that leads to the development if ischemic heart disease, disturbance of blood circulation in the brain. </p>

