            <p>Macromolecular colloid: when certain substances having big size molecules and large molecular masses, called macro-molecules, are dissolved in &#1072; suitable liquid, they form &#1072; solution in which the molecules of the substance in the dispersed particles have size in the colloidal range. These macromolecular substances are usually polymers with very high molecular masses. Examples of naturally occurring macromolecules are starch, cellulose, proteins, enzymes and gelatin. Examples of man-made macromolecules are polyethylene, nylon, polystyrene, synthetic rubber, etc. As these molecules have large sizes and have dimensions comparable to those of colloidal particles, their dispersions are called macromolecular colloids. Their colloidal solutions are quite stable and resemble true solutions in many respects. <br>
